<DOC><DOCNO> AP880329-0049 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 0427EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Volcano-Colombia     03-29 0157</FIRST><SECOND>PM-BRF--Volcano-Colombia,0162</SECOND><HEAD>Government Reduces Volcano Alert in Colombia</HEAD><DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Nevado del Ruiz volcano grew calmer,but the government insisted that people continue evacuating areasclose to the crater.   The volcano was spouting steam on Monday, but no ash was fallingin areas around the volcano, the government's National EmergencyCommittee said. Also, no tremors were being recorded.   The volcano started spewing steam and ash on Friday, becomingthe most active since it erupted Nov. 13, 1985, when 23,000 personswere killed.   People within a six-mile radius of the volcano were ordered toevacuate.   The Bogota newspapers El Tiempo and El Espectador reportedMonday that many people in small villages were refusing to leave.In Murillo, the largest village close to the volcano, Mayor JesusMaria Romero Aranzazu said only eight of the 600 residents therehad left, El Espectador reported.   Murillo, undamaged by the 1985 eruption, is five miles from thevolcano.</TEXT></DOC>